Abisola Olusanya, Lagos State Commissioner for Agriculture, has said that the attainment of food security is a major policy thrust of the Babajide Sanwo-Olu’s administration given its relevance in promoting the health and well-being of citizens and the achievement of the state government’s THEMES Agenda. She stated this on Thursday while speaking at the flag-off ceremonyforthedistributionof agricultural input and production assetstofishingandfarming cluster/communities, heldatthe Ikorodu local government area. She noted that the 2022 Agricultural Value Chains Enterprise Activation and Farmers’ Support Programme, which were flagged off, was designed to provide agricultural input and production assets to 120 fishing and farming clusters/ communities across the 20 local governments of the state. “In all, over 20,000 fisherfolks and farmers will benefit from the programme while budgetary provision has been made to accommodate a larger number of Value Chain Actors in the 2023 edition of the programme,” she said. She said one of the challengesconfronting agriculture inthe stateistheagingfarmerandfishermen populationandthat most youths who make up about 60 percent of the state’s population are not interested in agriculture asaprofessionbecauseof drudgery in the system. “It is in the wake of this fact, that the ministry partnered with innovative companies to introduce technology in agriculture, especially the upstream sector. “This is evidenced by the recently launched Tractor-on-the-Go project which is a tractor-hailing service designed to facilitate easy and affordable access to mechanization services through applications installed in mobile phones and integrated agricultural projects implemented in the state secondary schools tagged Lagos Agric Scholars Programme to stimulate the interest of school children in agriculture.” ‒‒:‒‒/‒‒:‒‒